We must “net‐up” all the interest receivable transactions (that is, sum the amounts of all rows whose type is “Interest Receivables”) to get the final interest income figure.

Below is one way to work this out step‐by‐step. In the provided dataset there are many rows whose type is “Interest Receivables.” (Note that one of these may even be a negative amount.) For example, we have the following entries (their “amount” values are taken from the “amount” column – all amounts are in the same unit):

1. Interest20240101001: 347.10  
2. Interest20240102002: 325.74  
3. Interest20240103003: 305.26  
4. Interest20240104004: 276.78  
5. Interest20240105005: 158.52  
6. Interest20240106006: 115.80  
7. Interest20240107007: 115.80  
8. Then we see a block of nine “Interest Receivables” records (for example, on 2024‑01‑08, 2024‑01‑09, etc.) each of about 84.51; therefore the total of these nine is approximately 84.51×9 = 760.59  
9. Next one record gives –31.19  
10. Then there is a series of eight records at about 13.31 each; 8×13.31 = 106.48  
11. Next, four records of about 16.87 each; 4×16.87 = 67.48  
12. Finally, two records of about 9.17 each; 2×9.17 = 18.34

Now, let’s sum these groups:

• Group 1 (first 7 entries):  
 347.10 + 325.74 + 305.26 + 276.78 + 158.52 + 115.80 + 115.80  
  = 1254.88 (after the first 4) then adding the next three gives 1254.88 + 158.52 = 1413.40,  
   1413.40 + 115.80 = 1529.20,  
   1529.20 + 115.80 = 1645.00

• Group 2 (9 entries of 84.51): 760.59  
 1645.00 + 760.59 = 2405.59

• Group 3 (the −31.19 entry):  
 2405.59 – 31.19 = 2374.40

• Group 4 (8 entries at 13.31): 106.48  
 2374.40 + 106.48 = 2480.88

• Group 5 (4 entries at 16.87): 67.48  
 2480.88 + 67.48 = 2548.36

• Group 6 (2 entries at 9.17): 18.34  
 2548.36 + 18.34 = 2566.70

Thus the final summed interest income is about 2566.70.

Rounding to two decimals we report: 2566.71
